aVI'm a molecular biologist by training,
p6
aVand I've seen a lot of these kinds of drawings.
p7
aVThey're usually referred to as a model figure,
p8
aVa drawing that shows how we think
p9
aVa cellular or molecular process occurs.
p10
aVThis particular drawing is of a process
p11
aVcalled clathrin-mediated endocytosis.
p12
aVIt's a process by which a molecule can get
p13
aVfrom the outside of the cell to the inside
p14
aVby getting captured in a bubble or a vesicle
p15
aVthat then gets internalized by the cell.
p16
aVThere's a problem with this drawing, though,
p17
aVand it's mainly in what it doesn't show.
p18
aVFrom lots of experiments,
p19
aVfrom lots of different scientists,
p20
aVwe know a lot about what these molecules look like,
p21
aVhow they move around in the cell,
p22
aVand that this is all taking place
p23
aVin an incredibly dynamic environment.
p24
aa(lp25
VSo in collaboration with a clathrin expert Tomas Kirchhausen,
p26
aVwe decided to create a new kind of model figure
p27
aVthat showed all of that.
p28
aVSo we start outside of the cell.
p29
aVNow we're looking inside.
p30
aVClathrin are these three-legged molecules
p31
aVthat can self-assemble into soccer-ball-like shapes.
p32
aVThrough connections with a membrane,
p33
aVclathrin is able to deform the membrane
p34
aVand form this sort of a cup
p35
aVthat forms this sort of a bubble, or a vesicle,
p36
aVthat's now capturing some of the proteins
p37
aVthat were outside of the cell.
p38
aVProteins are coming in now that basically pinch off this vesicle,
p39
aVmaking it separate from the rest of the membrane,
p40
aVand now clathrin is basically done with its job,
p41
aVand so proteins are coming in now \u2014
p42
aVwe've covered them yellow and orange \u2014
p43
aVthat are responsible for taking apart this clathrin cage.
p44
aVAnd so all of these proteins can get basically recycled
p45
aVand used all over again.
p46
aa(lp47
VThese processes are too small to be seen directly,
p48
aVeven with the best microscopes,
p49
aVso animations like this provide a really powerful way
p50
aVof visualizing a hypothesis.
