aVI spent months in Hollywood learning 3D animation software,
p66
aVand I spend months on each animation,
p67
aVand that's just time that most researchers can't afford.
p68
aVThe payoffs can be huge, though.
p69
aVMolecular animations are unparalleled
p70
aVin their ability to convey a great deal of information
p71
aVto broad audiences with extreme accuracy.
p72
aVAnd I'm working on a new project now
p73
aVcalled "The Science of HIV"
p74
aVwhere I'll be animating the entire life cycle
p75
aVof the HIV virus as accurately as possible
p76
aVand all in molecular detail.
p77
aVThe animation will feature data
p78
aVfrom thousands of researchers collected over decades,
p79
aVdata on what this virus looks like,
p80
aVhow it's able to infect cells in our body,
p81
aVand how therapeutics are helping to combat infection.
p82
aa(lp83
VOver the years, I found that animations
p84
aVaren't just useful for communicating an idea,
p85
aVbut they're also really useful
p86
aVfor exploring a hypothesis.
p87
aVBiologists for the most part are still using a paper and pencil
p88
aVto visualize the processes they study,
p89
aVand with the data we have now, that's just not good enough anymore.
p90
aVThe process of creating an animation
p91
aVcan act as a catalyst that allows researchers
p92
aVto crystalize and refine their own ideas.
p93
aVOne researcher I worked with
p94
aVwho works on the molecular mechanisms
p95
aVof neurodegenerative diseases
p96
aVcame up with experiments that were related
p97
aVdirectly to the animation that she and I worked on together,
p98
aVand in this way, animation can feed back into the research process.
